    "instruction": "Read metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv into pandas DataFrames and store them in kernel variables. For each file, return a compact summary containing: 1) total number of rows; 2) sorted list of unique cmdb_id values; 3) sorted list of unique kpi_name (for metric), trace_name (for trace), log_name (for log), or indicate 'message' for error_logs (limit each list to at most 50 entries); 4) minimum timestamp and maximum timestamp; 5) top 5 rows of the file. Keep outputs compact and textual. Do not print full datasets. Ensure results are returned as a small dictionary for each file." }

{
    "analysis": "The previous step computed global P95/P05 for 1760 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) series and flagged in-window points. The results show many degenerate cases where P95==P05==observed values and every in-window sample is flagged (likely because the KPI is constant or the quantile calculation produced identical thresholds). Therefore anomaly counts alone are not reliable. We need to prioritize series with meaningful deviation from their global thresholds (i.e., non-zero severity). One clear candidate from the summary is Mysql01 -> Mysql-MySQL_3306_Innodb data pending fsyncs: global P95=0 but high_max=1 in-window, producing a very large high_severity_pct — this merits focused inspection. Overall, Mysql01 series dominate the top anomaly counts but many are degenerate; we must select candidates by severity rather than raw anomaly count and then examine whether the anomalies form a consecutive fault (not isolated spikes).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the stored per-series summary (thresholds_per_series and the in-window anomaly flags), return a compact table of candidate series where the anomaly appears meaningful. Specifically: select series where (high_severity_pct > 0.0) OR (low_severity_pct > 0.0) OR (P95 == 0 AND window_max > 0). For each matching series return at most the top 20 rows sorted by max(high_severity_pct, low_severity_pct) descending. Include these columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, full_count, P95, P05, window_count, high_anomaly_count, high_first_ts, high_max, high_severity_pct, low_anomaly_count, low_first_ts, low_min, low_severity_pct. Also return a single scalar: the total number of series matching this filter. Keep output compact and textual." }

{
    "analysis": "Previous step computed global thresholds for 1760 series and flagged in-window anomalies. The raw anomaly-count ranking is dominated by many MySQL series where P95==0 and small nonzero in-window values produce huge numeric severity (artifact). A smaller set of non-artifact candidates (P95>0 and non-zero severity) emerged — notably ServiceTest9, ServiceTest8, ServiceTest5 (app.mrt), and Tomcat01 (CPU Wio and some disk metrics). To identify true faults we must find consecutive anomaly sub-series (streaks) rather than isolated spikes. If a candidate shows a multi-point consecutive breach (streak length >1) with meaningful severity (breach >> threshold or >50% of extreme), it becomes a likely fault and root-cause candidate. Next we should quantify per-candidate streaks (earliest/last flagged timestamps, longest consecutive streak length) for candidates with P95>0 and non-zero severity to prioritize those that form faults.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the stored per-series summary and the window-flagged rows, select series where P95 > 0 and max(high_severity_pct, low_severity_pct) > 0. For these series compute the following and return a compact table limited to the top 20 series sorted by max(high_severity_pct, low_severity_pct) descending: cmdb_id, kpi_name, full_count, P95, P05, window_count, high_anomaly_count, high_first_ts, high_last_ts, high_max, high_streak_max (longest consecutive run of values >= P95 within the window), high_streak_first_ts (start ts of that longest high streak) and equivalently low_anomaly_count, low_first_ts, low_last_ts, low_min, low_streak_max (longest consecutive run of values <= P05), low_streak_first_ts. Also return a short list (up to 10 entries) of series where high_streak_max >= 2 or low_streak_max >= 2 (these are likely faults). Keep outputs compact and textual; limit displayed rows to 20. Store full computed fault-streak table in a kernel variable for follow-up steps." }

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric-level and trace-level anomaly detection and fault-streak enumeration. Key observations: many ServiceTest* series show sustained anomalies but are not in the allowed root-cause component set and should be ignored. Among allowed components, metric anomalies with earliest timestamps cluster around ~22:01 (Tomcat01 CPU WIO and several trace anomalies involving Tomcat01, MG01, dockerA2/dockerB2) and another cluster around ~22:04 (Tomcat02↔MG02 traces). Trace anomalies with high severity frequently have first-high timestamps at ~22:01 and involve MG01, dockerA2/dockerB2, and Tomcat01 (trace.to_MG01.duration_mean and correlated MG01.from_Tomcat01). This suggests an early incident around 22:01 affecting calls between Tomcat01 and MG01/docker nodes. However, metrics also showed Tomcat01 local disk/IO and TCP FIN-WAIT anomalies (some at 22:01, some at 22:22). To decide the single root cause we must (per rules) focus on allowed components and identify the earliest faulty component whose fault is significant and is most-downstream among faulty services in traces. The next step is to consolidate metric anomaly evidence per allowed component to find: which allowed components had anomalies earliest (within the window), how many distinct KPI series were flagged per component, and the maximum severity per component. This will let us prioritize components (e.g., Tomcat01, MG01, Tomcat02, Mysql01/02, Redis01/02) and then correlate with the earlier trace anomalies to localize the most-downstream faulty service.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the stored metric per-series summary (thresholds_per_series/window_flagged_rows), restrict to allowed root-cause components: [apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02]. For each component compute: 1) earliest_anom_ts = the minimum of that component's series' high_first_ts and low_first_ts (ignore missing values); 2) flagged_series_count = number of (cmdb_id,kpi_name) series for that component with high_anomaly_count>0 or low_anomaly_count>0 in the incident window; 3) max_severity = maximum of high_severity_pct and low_severity_pct across that component's flagged series; 4) total_window_points = sum of window_count across its flagged series. Return a compact table sorted by earliest_anom_ts ascending, then max_severity descending, limited to top 20 rows. Also return a scalar: number of allowed components that have at least one flagged series. Keep outputs compact and textual." }

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric and trace anomaly scans and aggregated per-component summaries. Many metric anomalies are degenerate (P95==0) and likely artifacts, but a cluster of meaningful anomalies (non-artifact severity) appears around ~22:01+08 involving Tomcat01 and related traces (Tomcat01 ↔ MG01 and downstream docker nodes). Another cluster appears ~22:04 involving Tomcat02 ↔ MG02. Per rules, we must pick the root cause from the allowed components list and use traces to identify the most-downstream faulty service in the call chain. To do that we need the raw flagged trace samples (timestamps and values) for the candidate trace relations so we can see which component first shows increased latency and whether the anomaly propagates downstream. Logs can be consulted next, but first confirm temporal ordering and per-span values for these trace relations.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the kernel-stored trace window-flagged rows, extract raw flagged trace records (timestamp, timestamp_dt, cmdb_id, trace_name, value) within the incident window (timestamps >=1616680800 and <=1616682600) for these specific trace series: 1) Tomcat01 - trace.to_MG01.duration_mean, 2) MG01 - trace.from_Tomcat01.duration_mean, 3) Tomcat02 - trace.to_MG02.duration_mean, 4) MG02 - trace.from_Tomcat02.duration_mean. For each series return: a) count of flagged high points, b) earliest high timestamp (if any), and c) the raw flagged rows (limit to top 20 rows per series). Keep output compact and textual and store full extracted rows in kernel variables for follow-up. Do not print unrelated series." }

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric- and trace-level scans and identified two early clusters of anomalies: one around 22:01+08 (Tomcat01 <-> MG01 and several docker nodes) and another around 22:04+08 (Tomcat02 <-> MG02). The extracted flagged trace samples show Tomcat01.trace.to_MG01.duration_mean and MG01.trace.from_Tomcat01.duration_mean both have earliest high at 2021-03-25T22:01:00+08 with value ~0.988s, and Tomcat02↔MG02 have earliest high at 22:04 with value ~1.027s. Metric analysis (previous steps) showed Tomcat01 had non-artifact high severity for OSLinux-CPU_CPU_CPUWio at ~22:01 and some disk/network spikes later (~22:22). Many MySQL/MG metrics had extreme numeric severity due to P95==0 artifacts and must be treated cautiously. Per the localization rules, traces point to Tomcat01-related latency at 22:01 that is correlated with MG01 traces. To confirm whether Tomcat01 is the root cause (and whether it's CPU/WIO, disk IO, or network-related), we need raw metric samples for Tomcat01 around the earliest trace anomaly and also Tomcat01 logs in the incident window. Logs may indicate thread exhaustion, GC, OOM, or other runtime errors. The next step should therefore extract raw metric points for a focused set of Tomcat01 KPIs and the Tomcat01 log rows within the incident window for correlation.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From kernel-stored metric and log DataFrames, extract raw rows (timestamp, timestamp_dt, cmdb_id, kpi_name/log_name, value) within the incident window (timestamps >= 1616680800 and <= 1616682600) for cmdb_id == 'Tomcat01' as follows:\n1) Metrics: select these KPI name patterns (if present) — 'OSLinux-CPU_CPU_CPUWio', any 'LOCALDISK...DSKRead' and 'LOCALDISK...DSKRTps' for sda, any 'OSLinux-OSLinux_NETWORK_NETWORK_TCP-FIN-WAIT', and any Tomcat thread metrics (kpi_name containing 'Tomcat-Threads' or 'ThreadCount' or 'CurrentThreads'). Return the raw metric rows matching these patterns, and also provide a small aggregate per KPI: total rows in window, max value, min value, earliest timestamp of max, and count of values >= global P95 (use previously stored thresholds to flag). Limit raw rows displayed to at most 50 rows total (but store full extracted subset in a kernel variable).\n2) Logs: return all log.csv rows for cmdb_id == 'Tomcat01' within the same window (timestamp, timestamp_dt, log_name, value). Also return the count of error_count > 0 occurrences and the earliest timestamp when log.error_count > 0 (if any). Limit displayed log rows to 50 (store full in kernel variable).\nKeep outputs compact and textual. Do not print unrelated components. Store results in kernel variables for follow-up correlation." }

{
    "analysis": "We extracted Tomcat01 metrics and logs for the incident window. Findings: traces show Tomcat01 -> MG01 latency spikes with earliest high at 2021-03-25T22:01:00+08 (value ~0.988s). Tomcat01 metric anomalies (CPU WIO, disk reads, TCP FIN-WAIT) have their most significant metric spikes later (~22:22 for disk/CPU WIO), and thread/MaxThreads KPIs appear saturated (many samples equal to max) which could be instrumentation/threshold artifacts. Trace anomalies around 22:01 also involve MG01 and dockerA2/dockerB2 (MG01.trace.from_Tomcat01 and dockerA2 trace.*), with matching earliest high timestamps at 22:01. This temporal ordering suggests a latency event beginning at ~22:01 that involved MG01 (and downstream docker nodes) and was observed by Tomcat01 as elevated call latency. MySQL and many MG/Tomcat metrics show extreme numeric severity because P95==0 artifacts, so those need careful inspection. We have not yet confirmed whether MG01 is the root cause or merely a downstream victim; to decide we must inspect MG01 metric series for real resource anomalies (CPU, memory, disk I/O, network) that coincide with the earliest trace high at 22:01 and form consecutive faults (streaks). Logs for MG01 are not present, so metrics + traces are the primary evidence. Next step: inspect MG01 metric series (using previously computed global thresholds) and return compact per-series anomaly summaries and a few raw flagged rows for the top candidate MG01 KPIs so we can determine whether MG01 shows a real sustained fault starting at ~22:01. This will allow deciding root cause component, occurrence time, and underlying reason.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the kernel-stored metric thresholds and window-flagged rows, focus on component cmdb_id == 'MG01'. Produce a compact table (limit 20 rows) of MG01 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) series that meet any of: high_severity_pct > 0 OR low_severity_pct > 0 OR (P95 == 0 AND window_max > 0). For each series include: cmdb_id, kpi_name, full_count, P95, P05, window_count, high_anomaly_count, high_first_ts, high_max, high_severity_pct, low_anomaly_count, low_first_ts, low_min, low_severity_pct, and high_streak_max (longest consecutive run >=P95) and low_streak_max (longest consecutive run <=P05). Also return a short list (up to 5) of MG01 series with high_streak_max >= 2 or low_streak_max >= 2. For the top 5 series by max(high_severity_pct, low_severity_pct), extract and return the raw flagged rows (timestamp, timestamp_dt, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value) limited to 20 rows per series. Keep outputs compact and textual; store full extracted MG01 subsets in kernel variables for follow-up." }

